Omnia] According to the orthography that obtained in the days of Sallust, who flourished about the year of Rome 702, and in the time of the civil wars betwixt Pompey and J. Caesar, he writes omnis for omnes, alacris for alacres, communis for communes, civis for cives, hostis for hostes, urbis for urbes, and so of other nouns that have ium in the genitive plural. This, too, is frequently to be met with in Caesar and Cicero ; as also in Livy, Vix-gil, Horace, and other writers 'm the reign of Augustus—M.

³ Sed nostra] Sallust frequently uses the conjunction sed, not as an adversative, but as an inceptive or introductive particle.—M. Vide Gataker ad M. Anton. p. 282.—C.
